@andream5690 I mean I didn't really test it methodically to get a before and after comparison but basically: any game where you managed maybe 60Fps or less with DLSS performance at maybe medium settings will now run at far over 100+Fps at native res with max. settings. I tested it in a couple games like Kingdom Come Deliverance 1 (yes 1, not 2), the Dead Space Remake, Cyberpunk and I still play at 1440p and yea the performance gain is night and day. Personally I don't even care about RT but it's obviously also pretty fast at RT. But this depends a lot more on the game and how Raytracing is implemented. As an example I tested out Control again just for fun and at native resolution with RT you can change the RT settings so that even a 5070 Ti crashes down to 30Fps. Yes, at 1440p. This only happens tho if you put the RT sample rate to 8. Not sure exactly what that even does but if you set it to 8 it ANIHILATES your performance. If you leave it at 1 (hich hardly makes a difference, i looked at it, took screenshots etc.) it runs at like 100Fps 1440p, max. + RT. 

So short story: if you play at 1440p it's a night and day difference. Should a game run like crap on this card at 1440p it's either cause the game is horribly optimized OR cause it's a new graphics monster that sets a new standard for the next few years.

Also I got a 9800X3D and 32GB DDR5-6000 CL30-36-36-68 RAM and a 1000W PSU.

@andream5690 I played around a little with 8K and as an example: Cyberpunk 2077 runs at 40ish Fps in NATIVE 8K with all low settings. Might not sound that impressive cause all low but it is NATIVE 8K. it's not super high Fps but it's playable. Kingdom Come Deliverance 1 runs at medium settings at around 35Fps at 8K. Granted 8K is completely nonsensical BUT bot of those games look really good even at medium/low settings soooo...the fact that this card CAN play them at native 8K speaks for the performance I think. I paid around a grand so not exactly cheap but personally I just figured: "Who knows what will happen in the next 4 years? Who knows what NVIDIA will do?". Not just because of Trump but also because of rising issues with China and their threats towards Taiwan. And so I was just like "Eh, screw it". 
Maybe a 6070 Ti will release in early 2027 and it will offer, idk...70% more performance, 24GB VRAM for $699 or smth. Maybe. But it could also be +30% performance for an MSRP of $999 or smth.  Who knows. Personally I just bit the sour apple and I'm good for now for the coming years. I'm still interested in what happens in the hardware market but it doesn't have to concern me now.

Best is also to check out many different benchmarks for the 5070 Ti and then compare it to what you are getting and then make your decision on if it is worth it.
